WEBVTT

00:02.680 --> 00:18.205
This is a bright, sunny morning, March 30, and I 
have the joy and honor of being in the breakfast

00:02.680 --> 00:18.205
area just north of Moody with Dr. N.A. McNeil. I'm 
going to chat with him about his memories as a

00:18.826 --> 00:27.540
student and then as one of the dedicated members of 
the A&M staff. Dr. McNeil, try your, say a sentence

00:28.077 --> 00:32.323
or two and let's see your mics working. Now then, I 
was born in Moody. Okay, wait a minute. That's

00:36.910 --> 00:38.111
enough.

00:42.758 --> 00:50.289
Dr. McNeil, give us an autobiography of your days 
before you got to A&M. Where did you grow up and your

00:50.349 --> 00:56.518
family and what all did you learn growing up and 
that sort of thing? Well, My daddy was a dedicated

00:59.549 --> 01:13.441
Republican because he was related very distantly 
to General Sam Houston. And when Harding was

01:15.823 --> 01:23.070
elected, daddy expected to get the post office 
immediately. But it didn't happen that way. He

01:27.634 --> 01:29.235
rented our farm. to a distant cousin of his, and we 
moved into Moody after spending seven months as a

01:30.413 --> 01:43.509
farm overseer for a large landowner. After we 
moved to Moody, we still were not able to get into

01:44.871 --> 01:56.886
the post office until the last month of 19 and 22. At 
that time, as a 10, 12 year old boy, eight year old

02:00.704 --> 02:12.018
boy, I started working in the post office. And 
daddy would sort the mail into six stacks. And we

02:17.025 --> 02:20.429
had two stacks for local customers. And I put up the 
mail on the front part of the office while the

02:21.290 --> 02:30.542
carriers came in and took care of their various 
duties with the four stacks that he had prepared

02:31.754 --> 02:37.160
for them. After I got through with working in the 
post office with Daddy, I went to school. And for

02:47.171 --> 02:57.123
six months, they had to pay tuition for me because I 
was not quite old enough to go to school that year.

02:58.404 --> 03:00.867
But after we Got into the, after the election and 
while we were waiting for his appointment, I went

03:02.247 --> 03:15.067
to school at a rural school west of Moody at Haunted 
Hill. We had one teacher. And I suppose I started my

03:18.672 --> 03:22.418
teaching career there. Because when I went to 
Moody to school, I learned to read in the first

03:23.439 --> 03:29.689
grade. And when I got to Haunted Hill, the boys that 
was in the first grade with me had not been in school

03:30.665 --> 03:47.222
but maybe six weeks because they didn't start 
school till cotton picking was over. And the

03:48.383 --> 03:53.648
teacher who said to me, look, you've already read 
all of these books. You go over and listen to this

03:53.688 --> 03:59.254
other first grade teacher. first grade student as 
he learns to read.

04:07.248 --> 04:19.719
After I got back into the Moody School, I was 
interested at age 10 in 4-H club work. And it was

04:21.380 --> 04:29.207
several years after we got into 4-H club work 
before we got a vocational agriculture teacher at

04:21.380 --> 04:29.207
Moody. But I took part in that activity.

04:35.288 --> 04:52.692
Sometime in the early fall of 1930,

04:35.288 --> 04:52.692
one of my cousins came to me and said, look, you've 
just been in high school three years, but you've

04:35.288 --> 04:52.692
got as many credits in high school as I have. Let's 
go to A&M together next year. We'd been in 4-H

04:56.878 --> 04:58.620
together. So I said, well, all right. And we went 
down to A&M in April to the judging contest. We were

05:07.513 --> 05:15.545
dairy cattle judges, and we didn't place in the 
contest down there. But I went to the poultry farm

05:16.467 --> 05:22.817
and made application for a job. And soon after I got 
home, I was told that I could work on the poultry

05:23.878 --> 05:28.405
farm. In the meantime, I went down there and went to 
work on the poultry farm, but this cousin of mine

05:29.937 --> 05:44.632
could not finance in any way his going to A&M. He 
didn't have a job, and so he worked for Daddy in the

05:45.173 --> 05:56.164
post office for one year to get funds to go to A&M 
with me the next year. And Elsie and I went to A&M as

05:57.528 --> 06:08.021
part of the first project house that was ever 
organized at Texas A&M. Now, this was the fall of?

06:09.342 --> 06:10.764
31. No, fall of 32.

06:16.591 --> 06:22.058
In the meantime, there's other boys from Moody who 
wanted to go to A&M. And I came home and suggested

06:23.600 --> 06:26.303
that if we wanted to go to A&M that we organize a 
group and go down to A&M and get permission to have a

06:27.295 --> 06:40.930
group from Moody who lived off of the campus. And we 
went to see the Deans. And Dean Kyle was

06:46.056 --> 06:54.726
immediately in favor of the project for the boys to 
bring food from home and rent a house and live

06:46.056 --> 06:54.726
together. And Dean Winkler, who at that time was 
dean of the College of Education, knew my father

06:57.569 --> 07:09.582
through the association of being postmaster at 
Moody and his family there. So he said, look, this

07:10.363 --> 07:12.946
is great, we'll do it. When we went to see the other 
two deans, Dean Friley, and I don't instantly

07:14.208 --> 07:27.222
recall, I don't know the name of the other deans, We 
went to see Dean Francis. Of course, he was

07:32.097 --> 07:35.642
completely deaf at that time. And Dean Francis 
threw up his hands and says, whatever the rest of

07:36.523 --> 07:43.995
them decide, I'll go along with them. Thank you for 
coming. Two or three days later, we got a letter

07:46.699 --> 07:57.715
from Texas A&M addressed to my daddy saying that 
under two conditions, that you can do what you have

07:58.336 --> 08:01.781
asked to do. You must have someone to cook for you. 
You can't do that and come down here and batch. And

08:10.193 --> 08:16.922
the second condition was that you must have an A&M 
sponsor. We have that requirement for everybody.

08:21.549 --> 08:25.795
So Dan Russell, who made the talk, at moody the year 
that year before we approached the idea was asked

08:26.315 --> 08:49.048
to be the sponsor for the group and he was very 
graciously accepted the responsibility and did a

08:26.315 --> 08:49.048
great deal of work to get the house organized he 
found the cheap old house out near the Hort Farm

08:49.889 --> 08:56.255
that had been abandoned for 15 or 20 years. Horse 
farm? Hort. Horticulture farm. Oh, horticulture

08:59.979 --> 09:02.882
farm. He was called the Suber House. And it was 
ideally

09:05.425 --> 09:15.415
fitted to be a project house. There were four 
bedrooms upstairs. two bread rooms downstairs.

09:21.190 --> 09:25.894
They had a parlor, a kitchen, and a dining room. But 
they didn't have any water. And of course, they

09:30.218 --> 09:34.061
didn't have any bath facilities. So the parents of 
the boys, after we went down there, went down to A&M

09:35.022 --> 09:47.993
and replaced broken window lights, broken 
whatever they needed. And a well was dug by the

09:50.714 --> 09:55.980
landlord. And it was cased with pine casing. And 
you can imagine what that water tasted like when we

10:01.225 --> 10:10.675
had to make our meals with pine tasting water. But 
we piped the water into the bathroom and into the

10:11.816 --> 10:18.283
kitchen. And we lived in this house for 18 months. 
The first house was very, the first year was very

10:23.967 --> 10:29.373
successful. Who was the cook? Lena McMahon, 
M-C-M-A-H-A-N. McMahon sometimes it's called.

10:38.062 --> 10:39.184
Where did you all locate her? Well, she was a cousin 
of both A.A. McNeil and Ethel Aiken. mothers that

10:47.272 --> 10:53.420
went to A&M at the time that it was approved were on 
the steering committee that went to A&M. And she

10:54.902 --> 10:57.065
was a lovely person. And her husband came with her. 
He was unemployed at the time. And the first year,

11:04.836 --> 11:16.131
in August, when most of the students had gone home, 
Mr. McMahon was killed. on the road down to the

11:16.837 --> 11:20.261
horticulture farm. He was changing a tire on a 
truck and was killed. And after his death, then

11:25.387 --> 11:31.254
Cousin Lena wouldn't stay with us. We had to get 
someone else. And the next cook and caretaker was

11:34.958 --> 11:44.329
unhappy at A&M and said on the first of, january 
we're going back home to moody so that was the end

11:45.237 --> 12:14.535
off and by that time other project houses had been 
established and when those other houses were

11:45.237 --> 12:14.535
established most of the group went into the lufkin 
house and some of them went to the dormitory some of

11:45.237 --> 12:14.535
them went to independent but they scattered and 
the majority went to the lufkin house Do you

12:14.920 --> 12:20.446
remember what you and others brought from home in 
the way of food? We brought cured meat. We brought

12:23.810 --> 12:27.954
canned goods, home canned goods. And mostly it was 
canned, there was some canned meat that farmers

12:28.635 --> 12:36.344
had, the brothers had canned meat. But it was, we 
also purchased our necessary items from a local

12:44.080 --> 12:47.104
chain store. And Dan Russell was instrumental in 
locating this red and white store that gave us a

12:48.005 --> 12:55.274
nice discount. And we bought all of the necessary 
things other than that which we brought from home.

13:01.882 --> 13:03.344
One boy brought a cow. Every boy brought four hens. 
We had a chicken pen for all the eggs we needed. And

13:11.738 --> 13:17.286
we had all the milk that we needed from the cow that 
we brought from Moody.

13:20.971 --> 13:32.227
At the

13:20.971 --> 13:32.227
end of June, that was the second, third year, my 
third year in college.

13:35.312 --> 13:37.054
I had to go to summer camp.

13:40.156 --> 13:41.638
Cut it off just a minute. Complete. It's on now. 
Okay. After I had finished my junior year at A&M, I

13:47.306 --> 14:03.428
was able

13:47.306 --> 14:03.428
to get a contract. And with a contract, In military 
science, I got $31 a month. And after I got the $31 a

14:11.818 --> 14:17.647
month, I had to go to San Antonio for junior. 
Between my junior and senior year, I went to ROTC

14:18.288 --> 14:22.795
camp in San Antonio. I went to Camp Bullies. And we 
had to work from very early in the morning until

14:27.142 --> 14:33.332
noon, and then they dismissed us. And most of the 
A&M boys headed for San Antonio. And there were

14:37.409 --> 14:47.141
only three or four of us that were there in the 
afternoon because we didn't have any contacts and

14:37.409 --> 14:47.141
we didn't have any money and we stayed there. But in 
the meantime, I lost my contract if I did not take

14:48.523 --> 14:54.371
English. So I went to Tarleton to get the only 
school that I could find that offered English that

14:54.912 --> 15:03.403
I needed. And I enrolled in Tarleton, and the 
teacher in English was Pearl Mahan. And she saw

15:13.637 --> 15:22.450
three new students in her class, and she said, Ms. 
So-and-so, where did you take your English? And

15:23.611 --> 15:26.656
the student said, I took it at North Texas State. 
And Ms. Mahan said, what did you make? She said, I

15:30.301 --> 15:32.344
made an A. She said, if you work real hard, you can 
make a B here. And then she asked the second

15:38.563 --> 15:44.449
student, where did you take your prior English? 
And she said, I took it somewhere else. I don't

15:47.472 --> 15:48.273
remember. And then she said, Mr. McNeil, where did 
you take your prior English? And I said, Texas A&M.

16:00.117 --> 16:09.570
She said, Mr. McNeil, didn't you know that this was 
the hardest, that my English course was the

16:00.117 --> 16:09.570
hardest in the state? And I said, Ms. Mahan, I 
didn't know it till I got here. But anyway, she had a

16:16.620 --> 16:20.045
peculiar system of grading. I never understood 
it. I never questioned it. And I made a C, which

16:23.129 --> 16:26.033
would transfer to A&M. And another rather 
peculiar incident happened out there. Old Pop

16:30.205 --> 16:42.117
Hale had been teaching for years, and Pop Hale 
taught an education course, and so I enrolled in an

16:30.205 --> 16:42.117
education course. And the first day of class, he 
asked a question.

16:48.143 --> 16:55.150
It took me maybe decades of years to remember what 
question he asked. But the question he had to do

16:56.294 --> 17:06.229
with the peculiar kind of monkey that was found on 
the island of Madagascar. And when I answered that

17:06.249 --> 17:15.944
correctly, because I'd been reading the National 
Geographic, he called me Madagascar for the rest

17:06.249 --> 17:15.944
of the term. And at the end of that class, he called 
me in and said, I want you to grade my papers. And so

17:22.774 --> 17:24.597
in that Six weeks I was there, I graded Pop Hale's

17:25.420 --> 17:33.250
homework for him. I'd wait till the class was gone, 
get it, and then have it graded and ready for him to

17:33.371 --> 17:39.939
pass out the next day. Now this is at Tarleton? At 
Tarleton. Did you by chance ever hear any

17:42.843 --> 17:47.830
discussion of a former student of theirs named 
Earl Rudder? Not at all. The first time I heard the

17:50.633 --> 17:54.178
name Earl Rudder, had to do with wartime 
experiences. I had my wartime experiences in a

17:59.401 --> 18:05.947
different area than Earl Rudder had his. We'll get 
to those in a minute. At A&M, as far as you can

18:07.889 --> 18:16.476
remember, what did it cost for you to go to A&M? What 
was the tuition and fees when you were a freshman?

18:20.580 --> 18:21.120
Do you remember? $50. $50. For all? That was for a 
semester. Right. And where did you acquire that

18:27.927 --> 18:29.489
$50? Well, when my folks

18:30.690 --> 18:44.386
had to move away from the farm, I had a small dairy 
herd. And when we left the farm, I had to dispose of

18:45.768 --> 18:51.815
the dairy cattle. And I sent a load of cattle to Fort 
Worth. Eight head. And when I got the check, after I

18:59.676 --> 19:09.429
had paid the travel expenses and so forth in Fort 
Worth, I had $85. And I accumulated money from

19:09.449 --> 19:18.461
other ways until I had enough money to meet my 
expenses.

19:22.507 --> 19:23.548
I had money saved. that I used from various 
activities. Now to take the tape off, I want to tell

19:28.501 --> 19:32.968
you something else.

19:35.392 --> 19:37.275
Back to the project house. Describe the routine of 
duties that you and the other young men had in that

19:37.295 --> 19:44.586
project house. Who did what? Each pair of boys in 
one room had to keep their room clean. they had no

19:52.807 --> 20:16.097
other responsibility mrs mcmahan prepared the 
food they put it on the table and she did or her

19:52.807 --> 20:16.097
husband did the washing of the dishes in other 
project houses students were sometimes required

19:52.807 --> 20:16.097
to do part of the dishwashers and so forth, but not 
in any that I ever lived in. Did you all have any

20:21.123 --> 20:24.768
responsibilities for mowing the grass? Well, yes 
we did. One

20:28.253 --> 20:36.424
incident that we had, we had no sewer system. We 
built a privy with a deep hole out there and one

20:37.105 --> 20:45.477
morning when it got real cold, we looked out and 
there was smoke coming out of the privy. And sure

20:53.322 --> 21:03.995
enough, Mrs. McMahon's husband was out there with 
a bucket of cold to keep himself morning while he

20:53.322 --> 21:03.995
did his morning's morning. And one time, the rest 
of the boys got so annoyed with a couple of the boys

21:05.577 --> 21:12.966
that they were not keeping their room like it ought 
to be and so they each got little sticks and they

21:13.030 --> 21:40.810
went in that room and completely dismantled 
everything going around with their sticks saying

21:13.030 --> 21:40.810
i'm killing rats we're killing rats in this room 
and they didn't have any trouble with those fellas

21:13.030 --> 21:40.810
not keeping their room clean after that how did you 
all do your laundry uh we bundled all of our laundry

21:41.077 --> 22:10.847
up and took it down the road to a black woman who did 
the group the group laundry for everybody and it

21:41.077 --> 22:10.847
cost us maybe uh 50 cents a week to no more than 75 
cents a week to get everybody's laundry done and

21:41.077 --> 22:10.847
they it was a very satisfactory laundry situation 
In terms of food, it canned goods and cured meat,

22:11.384 --> 22:19.513
which would have been primarily pork? Yes, pork. 
Sometimes there was some canned meat from a beef

22:21.675 --> 22:27.742
animal. In some families, they'd kill a beef on the 
farm, and they didn't have the frozen food

22:28.603 --> 22:41.357
facilities then, so they'd can the meat that they 
couldn't cure. What about dessert? I really

22:46.341 --> 22:51.066
learned to do without dessert when we were in the 
project house. Did anybody bring any syrup,

22:51.326 --> 22:56.231
molasses, ribbon cane syrup from home? Not from 
this area. And do you remember how much this lady

22:59.335 --> 23:08.104
was paid as the

22:59.335 --> 23:08.104
hostess $1 per day. $1 per day. Well, $1 per month. 
Per boy? Per boy. And there were how many? There

23:17.659 --> 23:20.963
were 10 the first year and 12 the second. So you 
lived there two years. And in relation to the

23:23.966 --> 23:30.413
campus today, where was that house? The first 
house was right across the street from the

23:30.894 --> 23:35.859
horticulture farm. All right, but now. On the F&B 
Road. The Wellborn Road? No, it was the road that

23:44.350 --> 23:47.917
was going towards Snook? No, it was the road that 
went out by the dairy farm. and the horticulture

23:54.743 --> 23:58.767
farm, and it was called F&B Road. It was about a mile 
to the railroad crossing and another mile from the

23:59.668 --> 24:05.113
railroad crossing to the house. How did you and 
your buddies get from the house to the campus for

24:05.373 --> 24:09.357
class? Part of the time, we'd ride the truck that 
Mr. Mahan had. It was a big old gravel truck, and

24:18.266 --> 24:22.590
we'd ride in the back of that. Most of the time we'd 
walk up the railroad track and highway. Very

24:28.139 --> 24:32.364
seldom did we have to walk all of the way to A&M. At 
night, well, describe a typical weekday. What

24:38.311 --> 24:39.893
time did y'all get up? When did you go to class? 
What'd you do for fun? Well, we generally had

24:43.918 --> 24:49.725
breakfast at six o'clock in the morning. And then 
that gave us two hours to get to an 8 o'clock class if

24:50.431 --> 24:56.656
we had to walk all the way, but we didn't. We seldom 
walked all the way. And at noon, we were able to get

25:00.139 --> 25:08.066
back for a noon meal and our evening meal. We did not 
eat any meals away from there.

25:14.892 --> 25:20.337
We had football games and various other 
activities. that is confined to the 10 or 12 of us

25:20.806 --> 25:25.231
that were there. Now you were in the Corps. I was in 
the Corps and hated every day of it. All right, did

25:33.461 --> 25:36.424
you have to be over there to fall in for? The only 
time I went to the Corps was on drill day. They lined

25:44.133 --> 25:48.298
the day dodgers up on the second floor. And they 
beat the hell out of us. My tail end was as black as

25:53.421 --> 25:56.705
your hat. What did they use for paddles? It looked 
like shaved down baseball bats. It'd be as big

26:03.072 --> 26:08.678
around as a baseball bat, but it had flat ends. And 
what outfit were you in? I was in F company

26:11.621 --> 26:13.643
infantry. Did it have a nickname? Not that I know 
of, but it was made up of some of the better students

26:15.835 --> 26:24.028
at A&M that year. I remember that one of the Astons 
was in that organization. One of the Astons, from

26:31.019 --> 26:33.342
Brian? No. Who was that Aston? Oh, Jimmy Aston from 
Dallas. That's right. Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

26:41.495 --> 26:42.256
Farmersville. Right. And... Watson, the editor 
of the battalion, was in that unit.

26:51.230 --> 26:59.221
There were five of us that were seniors in F 
Company. And, of course, I was a second lieutenant

27:00.583 --> 27:06.791
because I hadn't been around all of the time. As far 
as I know, I'm the only living person that was in my

27:13.480 --> 27:17.004
senior class when I graduated.

27:19.386 --> 27:23.770
The third year, see I stayed in project houses for 
three years. Two years, because I'd stayed at the

27:25.953 --> 27:31.038
poultry farm one year and then project house two 
years. And then in the Corps, I waited on tables at

27:31.058 --> 27:37.745
the mess hall. And I was the only senior that waited 
on tables at A&M. Most of the supervisors were

27:44.092 --> 27:49.508
juniors and been there for some time. She'll get 
the phone.

27:55.966 --> 27:56.548
Honey?

28:11.345 --> 28:14.030
Now, you waited tables then in Sabisa? Right.

28:21.924 --> 28:28.917
My mama

28:21.924 --> 28:28.917
bought Lou Casey boots for me. Cost $35. And the 
seniors in my company decided I had not earned

28:33.198 --> 28:39.464
boots. And they were in my closet. And then they 
weren't. And I had to go buy a pair of $4 or $5 lace-up

28:46.852 --> 28:53.619
boots my senior year.

28:56.361 --> 28:59.865
And that's just... Did the Lucchese boots ever 
reappear? No. Oh, so somebody stole them. That's

29:02.367 --> 29:02.968
right. Somebody stole them, but they meant for me 
not to have senior boots as a day dodger. Now, were

29:11.761 --> 29:18.729
all project house students considered day 
dodgers? Until A&M built the 12 project houses,

29:18.749 --> 29:24.575
they were. When were those built? Was it after you 
were? It was about 1937. So after you were gone as a

29:30.782 --> 29:33.225
student. About how many project houses were there 
before A&M built some? At least 40. Did you all call

29:42.932 --> 29:45.777
them project houses then? Yes, sir. Did you all 
refer to your first one as the Moody Project House?

29:54.310 --> 30:01.160
We talked about it, but we also said Dr. Russell, 
D.R. Russell, said, had helped us, we put up a big

30:03.614 --> 30:07.159
sign, Russell Hall. Describe him and personality 
and type and everything. Well, Dr. Russell was a

30:15.130 --> 30:22.280
very compassionate man. And he did

30:22.320 --> 30:32.153
just a fantastic work with all of the project 
houses. but it was the Moody group that drew him

30:33.044 --> 30:38.252
into this. And the year that I was married in 1939, 
the radio

30:39.955 --> 31:00.148
program that was called the Inside Story

30:39.955 --> 31:00.148
called him when much publicity had been given to a 
Reader's Digest article saying that 2,000

31:00.668 --> 31:19.472
people, 2,000 students were going to school on the 
co-op plan which originated at Texas A&M with

31:00.668 --> 31:19.472
Daniel Russell. And he told them that he did not 
originate the plan, that I was a vocational

31:19.492 --> 31:28.363
agriculture teacher at Alvin, And he recommended 
they get in touch with me. And I got permission from

31:33.396 --> 31:37.780
the school board to go to Chicago. And I was told 
that I would stay at the Palmer House. And I thought

31:43.845 --> 31:48.189
that that was some little old side place.

31:52.793 --> 31:57.557
And when I found out it was the biggest hotel in 
Chicago, I went during the American Legion

31:58.212 --> 32:12.174
Convention, and they were dropping water in bags 
on people, and you couldn't get within four blocks

31:58.212 --> 32:12.174
of the hotel, and I had to dodge water bags to get to 
it. When I came home, I told them that we couldn't

32:13.557 --> 32:20.608
get in World War II, and that was in 1939. because we 
couldn't stand another crop of legionnaires.

32:28.558 --> 32:32.061
Let's see, back to that first year. Describe how 
you enrolled, signed up for your first classes

32:32.802 --> 32:39.968
that freshman year. What did you take that 
freshman year and why? Well, I took a regular

32:43.391 --> 32:51.017
course

