important to you later in your life?

34:13.983 --> 34:16.405
Well, sort of. but not my freshman year. I had an 
English teacher by the name of Keyes, if I remember

34:19.407 --> 34:25.292
correctly. Keyes, K-E-Y? K-E-Y-S. He had been an 
instructor at Thorpe Springs Christian College.

34:34.801 --> 34:43.710
And the most person who influenced me most at A&M 
was A.D. Martin, a math instructor. And he was, he

34:46.760 --> 34:49.583
was a member of the Church of Christ. And there was 
no building. And he came every Sunday morning and

34:52.786 --> 35:03.817
brought the Lord's Supper for a devotional in the 
YMCA. And on Sunday morning, I knew that I'd have a

35:05.158 --> 35:12.565
letter in the post office if I went to church. My 
mama had a letter. in the post office every Sunday

35:14.890 --> 35:17.135
morning. And I got acquainted with A.D. Martin. 
About how many attended that Church of Christ

35:20.662 --> 35:23.427
service? Well, probably 15 or 20. Were there other 
church groups meeting in the YMCA at various

35:30.441 --> 35:35.572
times? As far as I know, not. The Baptist Church had 
buildings just off of the campus. And the first

35:44.467 --> 35:57.542
year that Brother Martin was there, he went down to 
Houston to explain the church work that he did with

35:44.467 --> 35:57.542
students at A&M. And a woman by the name of Woodward 
told him that she wanted to build a church at A&M.

36:07.118 --> 36:09.462
and for him to get plans for a church. And when he got 
the plans and took it to her, it was a plan for a

36:10.763 --> 36:18.235
wooden building. And she said, that doesn't suit 
me. I want a brick building. And she was the wife of a

36:23.823 --> 36:26.667
wealthy oil man. And she says, I'll give you 
$10,000 a year for the next so and so. And so That

36:35.755 --> 36:38.620
building was built when I was a senior. So that was 
the first? That was the first building for the

36:40.763 --> 36:44.710
Church of Christ in College Station. That's 
right. And finished your senior year? I was down

36:48.916 --> 36:53.604
there quite often looking at the building. I 
watched them put every brick in it almost, but I was

36:53.704 --> 36:57.891
concerned. And I really, I don't know how to go 
about this, But Brother Martin gave me the cards

37:03.633 --> 37:13.269
for all of the people who said that they were 
members of the Church of Christ. And I carried

37:13.289 --> 37:17.516
those cards and made those contacts of all of them. 
And I knew by the time I was a senior, I knew nearly

37:18.257 --> 37:25.449
every one of the members of the Church of Christ. 
Were there many members off campus or were almost

37:25.469 --> 37:29.455
all of them students? There was only one person 
that ever came to that before church building. One

37:37.966 --> 37:43.151
of the employees, the USDA, would occasionally 
come to that service. And the others were

37:43.331 --> 37:47.235
students.

37:48.235 --> 37:52.359
And he brought the message each Sunday. That's 
right. And then he'd go back to Bryan and go to

37:55.142 --> 37:58.345
church in Bryan. Mm-hmm, mm-hmm. Did you by chance 
meet Mr. Cashin, who was the YMCA director? Oh,

38:03.401 --> 38:03.821
yes. Describe him, please. Well, he was just a fine 
individual, and he was compassionate, and he

38:05.323 --> 38:16.434
would do anything that he could for a student. I 
knew all of the people that worked at the YMCA for a

38:17.675 --> 38:28.686
period of time, but I don't really have any comment 
to make about him. I knew him quite well. Did you, in

38:35.257 --> 38:43.486
those days when you were living in the project 
houses, did you go into the A&M dormitories very

38:35.257 --> 38:43.486
often? Only when they took me in there when I was a 
freshman. I see. I did not go into, when I had drill,

38:51.415 --> 38:56.361
I didn't go into the dormitories. The only time I 
went into dormitories was to visit with members of

38:57.067 --> 39:01.854
the church. What about some friendships that you 
made during those early years that lasted

39:03.677 --> 39:08.544
forever? Who were some special fellow Aggies, 
special to you? Well, now then, the people that was

39:13.711 --> 39:25.048
in that first project cast evidently were made up 
of different background, and we've maintained

39:26.395 --> 39:30.583
contact. And in 1992,

39:31.625 --> 39:48.859
we had been out from A&M over these long periods of 
years, and we had a reunion here at Moody. And nine

39:49.497 --> 40:00.913
of the 18 who went to A&M in 1932, in the fall of 1932, 
met here at Moody for a reunion. About how many of

40:01.774 --> 40:04.919
the original group graduated?

40:07.462 --> 40:07.963
Half of them? Two-thirds? Oh, nearly all of them. I 
don't remember but one or two that didn't make it.

40:16.514 --> 40:22.721
We had one student from Moody that went down there 
and stayed a half a year nearly, and he couldn't

40:16.514 --> 40:22.721
make it. But I don't remember anybody else 
dropping out, and I don't remember anybody else

40:22.862 --> 40:29.429
that didn't graduate. When you went to and from 
Moody to College Station, how did you get there?

40:36.278 --> 40:38.100
Highway did. Road with them. Describe some 
memories you have of hitchhiking to and from A&M.

40:47.345 --> 41:02.144
Well, I can remember waiting on a corner in Marlin 
for 14 hours before a cotton truck came along

40:47.345 --> 41:02.144
loaded with cotton, and the driver told me I could 
sit on top of that cotton if I wanted to, and I did. In

41:02.244 --> 41:15.681
the four years that I went to A&M, I went back to A&M 
on rail no more than twice when the weather was,

41:17.045 --> 41:24.076
almost too bad to get if it wouldn't be anybody on 
the highway. Where could you catch that train? In

41:26.399 --> 41:26.940
Maryland? No, I caught the train in Moody and went 
to Milano, caught a change of trains there and went

41:27.401 --> 41:37.536
to Valley Junction and changed trains there and 
got to College Station. And I had two stops there.

41:42.256 --> 41:43.658
changes in between. Do you remember how much that 
cost? No, I don't have an idea. Did you ever have any

41:48.787 --> 41:51.412
bad experiences hitchhiking?

41:57.703 --> 42:03.994
I wouldn't call it bad experience, but I got in a car 
one time that was loaded with rifles. all kinds of

42:04.987 --> 42:06.849
artillery. And the people in it identified 
themselves to me as Texas Rangers, and they were on

42:08.030 --> 42:22.683
the route

42:08.030 --> 42:22.683
looking for Bonnie and Clyde. And I didn't, I got a 
ride and I was glad to do it, but the Texas Rangers

42:24.805 --> 42:34.133
picked me up one time, I remember. Which way were 
they headed? They were headed towards College

42:36.627 --> 42:38.409
Station. They'd let me out at College Station. Did 
you ever have any fun experience hitchhiking?

42:48.479 --> 42:49.000
Interesting? Goofy? Well, at the end of my 
freshman year, I hitchhiked all over Central

42:52.003 --> 43:01.032
Texas, from Moody to Goldthwait to Hamilton to 
back to moody and this spare country between the

43:01.265 --> 43:15.763
half of gold weight and hamilton i'll tell you that 
but i made it i had relatives living in mills county

43:01.265 --> 43:15.763
in comanche county And when you hitchhiked, you 
always wore your uniform. Yes, sir. Did not put up a

43:21.959 --> 43:24.261
sign or anything like that. Just rode your thumb. 
That's right.

43:29.506 --> 43:37.654
When you were going to class, how did you and your 
classmates, how did you all behave in A&M classes?

43:38.195 --> 43:41.398
There wasn't any question we behaved. And I want 
you to know that when I was an instructor at A&M, I

43:46.608 --> 43:54.442
never had a student that was any problem in 
conduct.

